="Continuum International Publishing Group" id="mwAdE">Continuum International Publishing Group</a>. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwAdI">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwAdM"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-8264-1628-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-8264-1628-5" id="mwAdQ">978-0-8264-1628-5</a><span class="reference-accessdate" id="mwAdU">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap" id="mwAdY">29 July</span> 2011</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Women%2C+Crime%2C+and+Punishment+in+Ancient+Law+and+Society%3A+The+ancient+Near+East&amp;rft.pub=Continuum+International+Publishing+Group&amp;rft.date=2004&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-8264-1628-5&amp;rft.au=Tetlow%2C+Elisabeth+Meier&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2F%3Fid%3DONkJ_Rj1SS8C%26pg%3DPA245%26dq%3DTashlultum%23v%3Donepage%26q%3DTashlultum%26f%3Dfalse&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASargon+of+Akkad" class="Z3988" about="#mwt194" id="mwAdc"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt194" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwAdg"/>
<cite class="citation book" about="#mwt199" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"title":{"wt":"Mesopotamia and the ancient Near East"},"author":{"wt":"Michael Roaf"},"authorlink":{"wt":"Michael Roaf"},"url":{"wt":"https://books.google.com/?id=SapVAAAAYAAJ&amp;q=Tashlultum&amp;dq=Tashlultum"},"publisher":{"wt":"Stonehenge Press"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-86706-681-4"},"year":{"wt":"1992"},"accessdate":{"wt":"29 July 2011"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAdk"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Michael_Roaf" title="Michael Roaf" id="mwAdo">Michael Roaf</a> (1992). <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/?id=SapVAAAAYAAJ&amp;q=Tashlultum&amp;dq=Tashlultum" id="mwAds"><i id="mwAdw">Mesopotamia and the ancient Near East</i></a>. Stonehenge Press. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwAd0">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwAd4"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-86706-681-4" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-86706-681-4" id="mwAd8">978-0-86706-681-4</a><span class="reference-accessdate" id="mwAeA">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap" id="mwAeE">29 July</span> 2011</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Mesopotamia+and+the+ancient+Near+East&amp;rft.pub=Stonehenge+Press&amp;rft.date=1992&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-86706-681-4&amp;rft.au=Michael+Roaf&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2F%3Fid%3DSapVAAAAYAAJ%26q%3DTashlultum%26dq%3DTashlultum&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASargon+of+Akkad" class="Z3988" about="#mwt199" id="mwAeI"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt199" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwAeM"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-53" id="cite_note-53"><a href="./Sargon_of_Akkad#cite_ref-53" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-53" class="mw-reference-text">Schomp 2005: 81</span></li><li about="#cite_note-54" id="cite_note-54"><a href="./Sargon_of_Akkad#cite_ref-54" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-54" class="mw-reference-text">Schomp 2005: 81; Kramer 1981: 351; Hallo, W. and J. J. A. Van Dijk. <i id="mwAeQ">The Exaltation of Inanna</i>. Yale Univ. Press, 1968.
</span></li><li about="#cite_note-55" id="cite_note-55"><a href="./Sargon_of_Akkad#cite_ref-55" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-55" class="mw-reference-text">Frayne 1993: 3637</span></li><li about="#cite_note-56" id="cite_note-56"><a href="./Sargon_of_Akkad#cite_ref-56" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-56" class="mw-reference-text">
"The black-headed peoples I ruled, I governed; mighty mountains with axes of bronze I destroyed. I ascended the upper mountains; I burst through the lower mountains. The country of the sea I besieged three times; Dilmun I captured. Unto the great Dur-ilu I went up, I<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwAeU"> </span>... I altered<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwAeY"> </span>... Whatsoever king shall be exalted after me,<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwAec"> </span>... Let him rule, let him govern the black-headed peoples; mighty mountains with axes of bronze let him destroy; let him ascend the upper mountains, let him break through the lower mountains; the country of the sea let him besiege three times; Dilmun let him capture; To great Dur-ilu let him go up." Barton 310, as modernized by <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.fordham.edu/halsall/ancient/2300sargon1.html" id="mwAeg">J. S. Arkenberg</a></span></li><li about="#cite_note-57" id="cite_note-57"><a href="./Sargon_of_Akkad#cite_ref-57" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-57" class="mw-reference-text">Bachvarova (2016:<a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=wxd-CwAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA182" id="mwAek">182</a>).</span></li><li about="#cite_note-58" id="cite_note-58"><a href="./Sargon_of_Akkad#cite_ref-58" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-58" class="mw-reference-text">Oates, John. <i id="mwAeo">Babylon</i>. London: Thames and Hudson, 1979, p.162.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-59" id="cite_note-59"><a href="./Sargon_of_Akkad#cite_ref-59" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-59" class="mw-reference-text">Sargon is the earliest known ruler with a Semitic name for whom anything approaching a historical context is recorded. There are, however, older references to rulers bearing Semitic names, notably the pre-Sargonic king Meskiang-nunna of Ur by his queen Gan-saman, mentioned in an inscription on a bowl found at Ur. In addition, the names of some pre-Sargonic rulers of Kish in the Sumerian king list have been interpreted as having Semitic etymologies, which might extend the Semitic presence in the Near East to the 29th or 30th century. See J. N. Postgate, <i id="mwAes">Languages of Iraq, Ancient and Modern. British School of Archaeology in Iraq</i> (2007).</span></li></ol></div></div>

